<h1 style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 16.1px 0.0px; font: 24.0px Times; -webkit-text-stroke: #000000"><span class="s1"><b>CS297 Proposal</b></span></h1>
<h2 style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 14.9px 0.0px; font: 18.0px Times; -webkit-text-stroke: #000000"><span class="s1"><b>AI-Powered Legal Decision Support System</b></span></h2>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">Alisha Rath (alisha.rath@sjsu.edu)</span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1"><b>Advisor:</b> Dr. Chris Pollett</span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1"><b>Description:</b></span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">The aim of this project is to develop an AI-powered legal decision support system using machine learning and large language models (LLMs). The system will be designed to predict legal case outcomes and sentencing based on initial filings, court documents, and transcripts. The first phase will involve developing a basic classification model using publicly available legal data and enhancing this model by integrating LLMs to extract detailed insights from legal documents for more accurate predictions.</span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1"><b>Schedule:</b></span></p>
<table class="border-table">
  <tr><td> Week 1: Sept 3 - Sept 9</td><td valign="top">Research legal case datasets and collect data relevant to charges and case outcomes.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 2: Sept 10 - Sept 16</td><td valign="top">Research legal case datasets and collect data relevant to charges and case outcomes.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 3: Sept 17 - Sept 23</td><td valign="top">Clean and preprocess the collected dataset for use in model training.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 4: Sept 24 - Sept 30</td><td valign="top">Develop a basic classification model to predict case outcomes (guilty/not guilty) based on charges.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 5: Oct 1 - Oct 7</td><td valign="top">Test and validate the classification model using a subset of the dataset.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 6: Oct 8 - Oct 14</td><td valign="top">Integrate large language models (LLMs) for summarizing court filings and legal documents.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 7: Oct 15 - Oct 21</td><td valign="top">Fine-tune the LLM for better accuracy in case outcome predictions based on document analysis.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 8: Oct 22 - Oct 28</td><td valign="top">Develop a method for evaluating prediction accuracy and adjust the model accordingly.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 9: Oct 29 - Nov 4</td><td valign="top">Write unit tests and integration tests for the implemented models.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 10: Nov 5 - Nov 11</td><td valign="top">Test the system with a variety of legal cases and validate results.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 11: Nov 12 - Nov 18</td><td valign="top">Start writing the project report and document the methods used.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 12: Nov 19 - Nov 25</td><td valign="top">Complete the project report draft and review it with the advisor.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 13: Nov 26 - Dec 2</td><td valign="top">Finalize and submit the CS297 project report.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 14: Dec 3 - Dec 9</td><td valign="top">Prepare a presentation for the project defense.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 15: Dec 10 - Dec 16</td><td valign="top">Present the CS297 project to the advisor and any reviewers.</td></tr>
  <tr><td> Week 16: Dec 17 - Dec 23</td><td valign="top">Review feedback and prepare for CS298 continuation.</td></tr>
  </table>
  
<p class="p3"><span class="s1"><b>Deliverables:</b></span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">The full project will be done when CS298 is completed. The following will be done by the end of CS297:</span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">1. Complete a tutorial on supervised fine-tuning, focusing on LLaMA 3.1 for AI models, and prepare 6-10 PowerPoint slides summarizing the findings from the tutorial and relevant papers.</span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">2. A cleaned and preprocessed legal case dataset for model training.</span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">3. Apply supervised fine-tuning using LLaMA 3.1 to classify the legal cases using the dataset collected above to decide a guilty or not guilty verdict.<span class="Apple-converted-space">Â </span></span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">4. Conduct experiments to assess the impact of varying the length of legal briefs on the training process and evaluate different fine-tuning methods.</span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">5. A completed CS297 project report and presentation.</span></p>
